# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: restconf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:restconf/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:restconf/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:restconf/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:restconf/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:restconf/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:restconf/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:restconf/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:restconf/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:restconf/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:restconf/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:restconf/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:restconf/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:restconf/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:restconf/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:restconf/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:restconf/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:restconf/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:restconf/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:restconf/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:restconf/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:restconf/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:restconf/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:restconf/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:restconf/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:restconf/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:restconf/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:restconf/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:restconf/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:restconf/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:restconf/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:restconf/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:restconf/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:restconf/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:restconf/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:restconf/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:restconf/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:restconf/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:restconf/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:restconf/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:restconf/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:restconf/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:restconf/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:restconf/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:restconf/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:restconf/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:restconf/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:restconf/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:restconf/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:restconf/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:restconf/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:restconf/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:restconf/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:restconf/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:restconf/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:restconf/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:restconf/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:restconf/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:restconf/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:restconf/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:restconf/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:restconf/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:restconf/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:restconf/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:restconf/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:restconf/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:restconf/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:restconf/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:restconf/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:restconf/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:restconf/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:restconf/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:restconf/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:restconf/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:restconf/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:restconf/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:restconf/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:restconf/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:restconf/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:restconf/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:restconf/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:restconf/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:restconf/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:restconf/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:restconf/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:restconf/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:restconf/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:restconf/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:restconf/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:restconf/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:restconf/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:restconf/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:restconf/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:restconf/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:restconf/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:restconf/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:restconf/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:restconf/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:restconf/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:restconf/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:restconf/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:restconf/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:restconf/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:restconf/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:restconf/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:restconf/netconf] The **Network Configuration Protocol** (**NETCONF**) is a network management protocol developed and standardized by the IETF.
[src:restconf/netconf] It was developed in the NETCONF working group and published in December 2006 as RFC 4741 and later revised in June 2011 and published as RFC 6241.
[src:restconf/netconf] The NETCONF protocol specification is an Internet Standards Track document.
[src:restconf/netconf] NETCONF provides mechanisms to install, manipulate, and delete the configuration of network devices.
[src:restconf/netconf] Its operations are realized on top of a simple Remote Procedure Call (RPC) layer.
[src:restconf/netconf] The NETCONF protocol uses an Extensible Markup Language (XML) based data encoding for the configuration data as well as the protocol messages.
[src:restconf/netconf] The protocol messages are exchanged on top of a secure transport protocol.
[src:restconf/netconf] The Operations layer defines a set of base protocol operations to retrieve and edit the configuration data.
[src:restconf/netconf] The Messages layer provides a mechanism for encoding remote procedure calls (RPCs) and notifications.
[src:restconf/netconf] The Secure Transport layer provides a secure and reliable transport of messages between a client and a server.
[src:restconf/netconf] The NETCONF protocol has been implemented in network devices such as routers and switches by some major equipment vendors.
[src:restconf/netconf] One particular strength of NETCONF is its support for robust configuration change using transactions involving a number of devices.
[src:restconf/netconf] The IETF developed the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) in the late 1980s and it proved to be a very popular network management protocol.
[src:restconf/netconf] In the early part of the 21st century it became apparent that in spite of what was originally intended, SNMP was not being used to configure network equipment, but was mainly being used for network monitoring.
[src:restconf/netconf] In June 2002, the Internet Architecture Board and key members of the IETF's network management community got together with network operators to discuss the situation.
[src:restconf/netconf] The results of this meeting are documented in RFC 3535.
[src:restconf/netconf] It turned out that each network operator was primarily using a different proprietary command-line interface (CLI) to configure their devices.
[src:restconf/netconf] This had a number of features that the operators liked, including the fact that it was text-based, as opposed to the BER-encoded SNMP.
[src:restconf/netconf] In addition, many equipment vendors did not provide the option to completely configure their devices via SNMP.
[src:restconf/netconf] As operators generally liked to write scripts to help manage their boxes, they found the SNMP CLI lacking in a number of ways.
[src:restconf/netconf] Most notably was the unpredictable nature of the output.
[src:restconf/netconf] The content and formatting of output was prone to change in unpredictable ways.
[src:restconf/netconf] Around this same time, Juniper Networks had been using an XML-based network management approach.
[src:restconf/netconf] This was brought to the IETF and shared with the broader community.
[src:restconf/netconf] Collectively, these two events led the IETF in May 2003 to the creation of the NETCONF working group.
[src:restconf/netconf] This working group was chartered to work on a network configuration protocol, which would better align with the needs of network operators and equipment vendors.
[src:restconf/netconf] The first version of the base NETCONF protocol was published as RFC 4741 in December 2006.
[src:restconf/netconf] Several extensions were published in subsequent years (notifications in RFC 5277 in July 2008, partial locks in RFC 5717 in December 2009, with-defaults in RFC 6243 in June 2011, system notifications in RFC 6470 in February 2012, access control in RFC 6536 in March 2012).
[src:restconf/netconf] A revised version of the base NETCONF protocol was published as RFC 6241 in June 2011.
[src:restconf/netconf] The content of NETCONF operations is well-formed XML.
[src:restconf/netconf] Most content is related to network management.
[src:restconf/netconf] Subsequently, support for encoding in JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) was also added.
[src:restconf/netconf] The NETMOD working group has completed work to define a "human-friendly" modeling language for defining the semantics of operational data, configuration data, notifications, and operations, called YANG.
[src:restconf/netconf] YANG is defined in RFC 6020 (version 1) and RFC 7950 (version 1.1), and is accompanied by the "Common YANG Data Types" found in RFC 6991.
[src:restconf/netconf] During the summer of 2010, the NETMOD working group was re-chartered to work on core configuration models (system, interface, and routing) as well as work on compatibility with the SNMP modeling language.
[src:restconf/netconf] Basic NETCONF functionality can be extended by the definition of NETCONF capabilities.
[src:restconf/netconf] The set of additional protocol features that an implementation supports is communicated between the server and the client during the capability exchange portion of session setup.
[src:restconf/netconf] Mandatory protocol features are not included in the capability exchange since they are assumed.
[src:restconf/netconf] RFC 4741 defines a number of optional capabilities including :xpath and :validate.
[src:restconf/netconf] A capability to support subscribing and receiving asynchronous event notifications is published in RFC 5277.
[src:restconf/netconf] This document defines the <create-subscription> operation, which enables creating real-time and replay subscriptions.
[src:restconf/netconf] Notifications are then sent asynchronously using the <notification> construct.
[src:restconf/netconf] It also defines the :interleave capability, which when supported with the basic :notification capability facilitates the processing of other NETCONF operations while the subscription is active.
[src:restconf/netconf] A capability to support partial locking of the running configuration is defined in RFC 5717.
[src:restconf/netconf] This allows multiple sessions to edit non-overlapping sub-trees within the running configuration.
[src:restconf/netconf] Without this capability, the only lock available is for the entire configuration.
[src:restconf/netconf] A capability to monitor the NETCONF protocol is defined in RFC 6022.
[src:restconf/netconf] This document contains a data model including information about NETCONF datastores, sessions, locks, and statistics that facilitates the management of a NETCONF server.
[src:restconf/netconf] It also defines methods for NETCONF clients to discover data models supported by a NETCONF server and defines the <get-schema> operation to retrieve them.
[src:restconf/netconf] Every NETCONF message is a well-formed XML document.
[src:restconf/netconf] An RPC result is linked to an RPC invocation by a message-id attribute.
[src:restconf/netconf] NETCONF messages can be pipelined, i.e., a client can invoke multiple RPCs without having to wait for RPC result messages first.
[src:restconf/netconf] RPC messages are defined in RFC 6241 and notification messages are defined in RFC 5277.
[src:restconf/network-management] A number of applications and protocols exist to support network and network device management.
[src:restconf/network-management] Network management allows IT professionals to monitor network components within a large network area.
[src:restconf/network-management] Access methods include the SNMP, command-line interface (CLI), custom XML, CMIP, Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), Transaction Language 1 (TL1), CORBA, NETCONF, RESTCONF and the Java Management Extensions (JMX).
[src:restconf/network-management] Schemas include the Structure of Management Information (SMI), YANG, WBEM, the Common Information Model (CIM Schema), and MTOSI amongst others.
[src:restconf/network-management] Effective network management can provide positive strategic impacts.
[src:restconf/network-management] For example, in the case of developing an infrastructure, providing participants with some interactive space allows them to collaborate with each other, thereby promoting overall benefits.
[src:restconf/network-management] At the same time, the value of network management to the strategic network is also affected by the relationship between participants.
[src:restconf/network-management] Active participation, interaction and collaboration can make them more trusting of each other and enhance cohesion.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:restconf/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:restconf/yang] YANG enables comprehensive network automation by providing a standardized way to model the configuration and state data of network elements.
[src:restconf/yang] The language can be used to define the format of event notifications emitted by network devices and allows data modelers to define the signature of RPCs that can be invoked on network elements via the NETCONF protocol.
[src:restconf/yang] Being protocol-independent, YANG models can be converted into various encoding formats, including XML, JSON, and CBOR, depending on the network configuration protocol's support.
[src:restconf/yang] YANG is a modular language and represents data structures in a hierarchical tree format.
[src:restconf/yang] It includes numerous built-in data types, with the capability for users to derive additional application-specific types.
[src:restconf/yang] More complex reusable data structures can be represented as "groupings," which promote model reusability and consistency.
[src:restconf/yang] YANG data models can use XPath expressions to define constraints on the elements of a YANG data model, enabling validation of configuration data before it is committed to devices.
[src:restconf/yang] YANG has become the de facto standard for modeling network device configurations across the telecommunications industry and is widely supported by major network equipment manufacturers.
[src:restconf/yang] It plays a crucial role in software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) environments by providing a consistent interface for programmatic network management.
[src:restconf/yang] Many network management protocols have associated data modeling languages.
[src:restconf/yang] The first widely deployed Internet standard for network management was the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
[src:restconf/yang] The data modeling language associated with SNMP was called the Structure of Management Information (SMI).
[src:restconf/yang] The SMI language itself was based on the 1988 version of the Abstract Syntax Notation One (ASN.1).
[src:restconf/yang] The current version of the SMI language, SMIv2 defined in RFC 2578, 2579 and 2580, has developed into an extended subset of ASN.1.
[src:restconf/yang] In the late 1990s, a project was started to create a replacement for SMIv2, which was called SMIng.
[src:restconf/yang] One motivation was to decouple SMIng from the management protocol SNMP and to give SMIng a syntactic structure that is both easy to parse for computer programs and easy to learn for people familiar with programming languages that use a C-like notation.
[src:restconf/yang] While the SMIng project did not succeed in the IETF, the SMIng specifications were published as experimental documents in May 2004 (RFC 3780, 3781).
[src:restconf/yang] Soon after the development of the NETCONF protocol in the IETF, it became clear that a data modeling language was needed to define data models manipulated by the NETCONF protocol.
[src:restconf/yang] A design team created a proposal that became the basis of the YANG language.
[src:restconf/yang] The syntactic structure and the base type system was essentially borrowed from SMIng.
[src:restconf/yang] However, based on the lessons learned from the SMIng project, no attempts were made to make the YANG protocol neutral.
[src:restconf/yang] Instead, YANG ties into concepts of the NETCONF protocol, such as the assumption that data model instances can be serialized into XML.
[src:restconf/yang] Standardization of YANG started with the formation of the NETMOD working group in April 2008.
[src:restconf/yang] The YANG 1.0 specification was published as RFC 6020 in October 2010.
[src:restconf/yang] Recently, the NETMOD working group has been working on YANG 1.1, which has been published in August 2016 in RFC 7950.
[src:restconf/yang] The following YANG module `example-sports` shows a data model for team sports.
[src:restconf/yang] The module declares a namespace and a prefix and imports the type library module `ietf-yang-types` before defining the type `season`.
[src:restconf/yang] It then defines a container `sports` that includes a list of `person`s and a list of `team`s.
[src:restconf/yang] A team has a list of players that reference persons via the `leafref` type and its `path` restriction.
[src:restconf/yang] The code block below shows the JSON representation of an instantiation of the `example-sports` data model.
